      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Version-controlled solver with documented release notes and regression test suite.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022R2 is used under a validated configuration management plan. Regression tests confirm solver build integrity. Achieved level meets the MRL 2 requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver passes published benchmark cases relevant to rotating-frame turbulent flow.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent passes the lid-driven cavity and Taylor-Couette benchmark cases documented in the solver verification report. No custom user-defined functions were introduced."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) below 5% for the primary quantity of interest (relative hemolysis index RH) across all five operating points, with formal Richardson extrapolation on three systematically refined meshes.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted with coarse (4.1M), medium (9.8M), and fine (18.6M) element counts. Richardson extrapolation yields GCI values of 3.8–7.2% depending on operating point; the highest GCI of 7.2% at the low-flow high-speed condition marginally exceeds the 5% threshold. The team judged this exceedance acceptable because the operating point in question produces RH values well below unity, and the direction of the discretization error is conservative (over-predicts hemolysis). Formal GCI documentation covers only two of the three required refinement ratios, placing the achieved level at Gradation 2 rather than the required Gradation 3. Supplementary mesh sensitivity plots were submitted to support the acceptance decision."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions (inlet flow rate, rotational speed, fluid viscosity) reproduced within ±3% of nominal values.",
      "rationale": "FDA pump experimental conditions are replicated to within 1.5% for flow rate and 0.8% for rotational speed. Fluid viscosity is matched using a phosphate-buffered saline-glycerol surrogate calibrated at 37°C."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted RH within ±15% of experimentally measured values at all five operating points.",
      "rationale": "Predicted relative hemolysis index deviates from experimental measurements by 4–12% across the five operating points. All comparisons fall within the ±15% acceptance band. Uncertainty bars are reported for both simulation and experiment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Primary QoI (RH) directly maps to the clinical acceptance criterion and is mechanistically linked to the hemolysis power-law model.",
      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index is the regulatory QoI for CPB pump submissions. The power-law hemolysis model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger) is applied to scalar stress histories extracted from particle tracks, providing a direct mechanistic connection between CFD outputs and the clinical metric."
    },
